President Trump made remarks at Joint Base Andrews in Maryland regarding the shooting at the Tree of Life synagogue in Squirrel Hill, Pittsburgh. He expressed his condolences and spoke about the need to address hate and violence in the country and around the world. Trump mentioned that the results of the shooting were more devastating than initially thought and praised law enforcement for their response. When asked about gun laws, he suggested that having armed guards inside places of worship could potentially prevent such incidents. He also mentioned the possibility of stiffening laws and bringing back the death penalty for those who commit such acts of violence. Trump acknowledged that it is unfortunate to have to think about such security measures but emphasized the importance of protection. He mentioned having conversations with the NRA and stated that they are always talking.